messages.message: JW: Why is there no `release-25.08.0-aihub` branch in git?

Or more to the point, why was it moved to:

```owner@dev:~/instabase/shared-utils/go-utils/src/instabase/utils/db$ git branch -r | grep 25.08
  origin/DEPRECATED_release-25.08.0-aihub```
?
Might be part of the github branches that @Cody Boggs has been cleaning up

:wave: 25.08 is no longer in the supported release version window, and thus was deprecated as part of this week's code-cut of 25.14. :slightly_smiling_face:

Announced here (https://instabase.slack.com/archives/C06FA6A23/p1742494977924249) a bit ago, but I know it's crazy busy and noisy lately - easy to miss!

You can also reference the list pinned at the top of <#C041XGH39UN|> that is updated on the code-cut cadence.
release-25.06.0 is still present though btw

That said the tags still exist for that release, and the code cut procedure (https://github.com/instabase/instabase/blob/master/releng/docs/release-coordinator/code-cut.md#5-deprecation-and-cleanup-of-old-releases) accounts for 'uh oh' moments (of which we've had a couple just this week! :slightly_smiling_face:) such that we can resurrect the branch by renaming it back to the normal convention. It isn't deleted until the _next_ code cut

Yes - there was an ask to bring 25.06 back a couple days ago (for the db checkpoint incident I think? I forget), and it's initial deprecation was already delayed due to a separate incident last round. :+1:
Can certainly put 25.08 back in place if it will unblock you!

There are a few inconsistencies here:

release-25.06.0 branch is still present
release-25.08.0 branch is not present

release-25.10.0 branch doesn't have a 25.10.0 tag (maybe 25.10.1 was the first point release that certified in this case?)

I think when we deprecate a branch, we should tag the last point release so it's easy to find in investigations like the one I was doing this AM
BTW, I am not blocked -- was just confused.

Very fair. :joy:
It's not something that has been formalized or diligently reconciled in the past, so we've adjusted a bit. If it ends up being too much or too constrained, happy to refine. :slightly_smiling_face:
